"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715583","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-24","<p>The National Planning Policy Framework requires local planning authorities to identify a supply of deliverable sites sufficient to provide five years' worth of housing against their housing requirements. We do not hold information centrally on how many authorities have a deliverable five-year housing land supply because the position changes frequently, as it is subject to market conditions.</p><p>The Housing White Paper includes a proposal to offer greater certainty to local planning authorities, developers and communities by enabling authorities to consult with key stakeholders and agree their housing land supply with the Planning Inspectorate. This would then be fixed for a one-year period.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","69970","2017-04-24T14:36:58.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715583/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715583/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-30","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many local authorities in England have a deliverable five year housing land supply as required by the National Planning Policy Framework.","false","Biography information for Alistair Burt","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","69969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715584","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-24","<p>The National Planning Policy Framework requires local planning authorities to identify a supply of deliverable sites sufficient to provide five years' worth of housing against their housing requirements. We do not hold information centrally on how many authorities have a deliverable five-year housing land supply because the position changes frequently, as it is subject to market conditions.</p><p>The Housing White Paper includes a proposal to offer greater certainty to local planning authorities, developers and communities by enabling authorities to consult with key stakeholders and agree their housing land supply with the Planning Inspectorate. This would then be fixed for a one-year period.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","69969","2017-04-24T14:36:58.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715584/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715584/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-30","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many local authorities in England have 90 per cent of a deliverable five year housing land supply as required by the National Planning Policy Framework.","false","Biography information for Alistair Burt","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","69970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715585","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-18","<p>Planning guidance is clear that Local Planning Authorities should ensure turbines are removed when no longer in use and land is restored to an appropriate use. Local Planning Authorities can use planning conditions to ensure this happens. Wind farms, like other developments granted planning permission must be constructed and operated according to the decision notice issued and any specific conditions attached to the notice.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-18T11:55:05.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715585/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715585/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-30","Wind Power: Decommissioning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his policy is on the decommissioning of windfarms.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","69944"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715586","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-20","<p>Whilst no outturn data for the amount paid in rates by businesses in Newham are held centrally for the years before and after revaluation, forecasts are available. According to Newham's own forecast on their National Non-Domestic Return 1 for 2016-17, businesses paid a total of £133 million after reliefs.</p><p>They forecast this to increase to £142 million according to their National Non-Domestic Return 1 for 2017-18. This increase is affected by revaluation, inflation, changes in business rate relief policy, changes in the number and value of properties entitled to business rate reliefs and changes in the tax base.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-20T14:24:46.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715586/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715586/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715586/answer/previousversion/44425","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-30","Non-domestic Rates: Newham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 22 March 2017 to Question 68303, on non-domestic rates: Newham, if he will make it his policy to collect data on the amount of rates paid by businesses in the London Borough of Newham.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","69943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715587","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-24","<p>It is our National Planning Policy Framework, not regulation, that defines brownfield. This states clearly that, if a site is brownfield, it should not be assumed that the whole curtilage should be developed. Whilst this Government is keen to ensure the re-use of brownfield sites that are not of high environmental value, especially for new homes, it would be for the local authority to decide whether an airfield should be retained for general aviation; whether a site, or part of a site, is suitable for redevelopment; and whether former airfield land should be retained for uses such as nature conservation, recreation or agriculture.</p><p>The local authority should have regard to all relevant policies in the National Planning Policy Framework including, where relevant, the policy for airports and airfields (that are not subject to a separate national policy statement) which expects local planning authorities to take account of their growth and role in serving business, leisure, training and emergency needs.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-24T14:32:20.99Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715587/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715587/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-30","Airports: Vacant Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he plans to take to reclassify the status of airfields to greenfield under planning regulations.","false","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","69994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715588","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-18","<p>My Department has no plans to carry out an assessment, but we are carefully reviewing the case for reform of the private parking sector.</p><p>The Information Commissioner’s Office carried out an audit in March 2016, and judged the DVLA’s procedures to offer high assurance that processes to mitigate the risks of non-compliance with the Data Protection Act are in place.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-04-18T10:39:20.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715588/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715588/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715588/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-30","Parking: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make it his policy to carry out an assessment of the effect on privacy and industry regulation of the practice of private car parking companies distributing third parties information from the DVLA vehicle keeper database.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","70213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715589","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-18","<p>There have been 401 successful applications in Derbyshire to date, and 147 installations have been made following these applications. We do not have a breakdown of applications at constituency level.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-04-18T09:21:17.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715589/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715589/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715589/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-30","Broadband: High Peak","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many successful applications for the Better Broadband Subsidy Scheme there have been in High Peak constituency since that scheme's introduction.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bingham","High Peak","Andrew Bingham","70199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715590","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-18","<p>UK Anti-Doping (UKAD) collaborates with a number of partners including National Governing Bodies of sport, law enforcement and Government departments to help prevent doping in sport. Central to this approach is anti-doping education, which is vital at all levels of sport. We would encourage every sport to invest more into preventing doping in sport and ensure that they have a robust anti-doping strategy in place to safeguard their sport from elite level to grassroots.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, Government is undertaking its requisite triennial review on UKAD and its functions. The review will consider the efficiency, effectiveness and governance of UKAD and how it is preparing for the future. As part of the review a call for evidence was launched on 30 March.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-04-18T09:17:29.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715590/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715590/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715590/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-30","Sports: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 27 March 2017 to Question 68575, on sports: drugs, if she will specify what steps her Department is taking to prevent doping in amateur competitive sport.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","69981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715591","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-19","<p>The Government has a long term plan and strategy to make sure that the sector is supported. Given the sector’s diversity, we recognise that there could be a broad range of implications and we are carefully assessing the impact of leaving the EU on the voluntary and community sector. We are also continuing to gather information and listen to the concerns and priorities of the charity sector.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-04-19T11:10:57.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715591/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715591/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715591/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-30","Charities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment she has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on (a) access to funding for the charity sector and (b) the charity sector in general.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","69960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715592","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-18","<p>National Governing Bodies are expected to have an agreed plan in place with UK Sport and Sport England, which sets out how they will meet the governance code reforms, by April 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The plans need to set out how they will comply with all aspects of the code by 31st October 2017.</p><p> </p><p>NGBs will not receive any funding from UK Sport or Sport England until their plans have been agreed by both organisations. Funding will also be contingent on NGBs being fully compliant with the code by 31st October.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-04-18T09:18:50.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715592/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715592/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715592/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-30","Sports: Governing Bodies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, by what date sports national governing bodies are required to enact all necessary reforms set out under the new national code for sports governance.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","69952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715593","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-19","<p>Civil Servants have to ability to work flexibly across government sites where there is a business need to do so. The issuing of all passes is controlled by the local Departmental Security teams who follow strict procedures and protocols. DCMS does not manage the local Security team for its main premises, that is done by HMT.</p><p>Therefore the information requested is not centrally held by the department.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","70036 ; 70057","2017-04-19T08:44:26.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715593/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715593/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715593/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-30","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many security passes giving access to her Department's premises are currently valid.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715594","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-19","<p>This information is available in the ONS Public Sector Employment Statistics last published on 15 March 2017:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/publicsectoremploymentreferencetableBackground" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/publicsectoremploymentreferencetableBackground</a></p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-04-19T08:45:12.57Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715594/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715594/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-30","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many people are currently employed by her Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715595","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-19","<p>Civil Servants have to ability to work flexibly across government sites where there is a business need to do so. The issuing of all passes is controlled by the local Departmental Security teams who follow strict procedures and protocols. DCMS does not manage the local Security team for its main premises, that is done by HMT.</p><p>Therefore the information requested is not centrally held by the department.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","70019 ; 70036","2017-04-19T08:44:26.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715595/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715595/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715595/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-30","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many people holding security passes for other Government Departments are granted access to her Department's premises with that pass, by Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715596","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-19","<p>Civil Servants have to ability to work flexibly across government sites where there is a business need to do so. The issuing of all passes is controlled by the local Departmental Security teams who follow strict procedures and protocols. DCMS does not manage the local Security team for its main premises, that is done by HMT.</p><p>Therefore the information requested is not centrally held by the department.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","70019 ; 70057","2017-04-19T08:44:26.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715596/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715596/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715596/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-30","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many security passes giving access to her Department's premises have been issued in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715597","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-18","<p>The same rules and laws will apply on the day after Brexit as they did before, including for roaming.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-04-18T09:46:36.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715597/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715597/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715597/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-30","Telephone Services: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department has undertaken any research on the effect of the UK leaving the EU on consumer phone bills and mobile roaming charges.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","70149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715598","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-19","<p>The information on numbers of security passes issued is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-19T16:16:45.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715598/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715598/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715598/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Ministry of Defence: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many security passes giving access to his Department's premises have been issued in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715599","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-19","<p>Civil Servants have the ability to work flexibly across Government sites where there is a business need to do so. The issuing of all passes is controlled by the local Departmental security teams who follow strict procedures and protocols. Information on the number of people holding security passes for other Government departments who are granted access to the Ministry of Defence premises is not centrally recorded.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-19T16:14:09.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715599/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715599/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715599/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Ministry of Defence: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many people holding security passes for other Government Departments are granted access to his Department's premises with that pass, by Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715600","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-19","<p>As of 1 January 2017 the total headcount of the Ministry of Defence (MOD) civilian personnel strength was 57,870.</p><p> </p><p>This information is published within the MOD quarterly civilian personnel statistics report 2017 which can be found on the Gov.uk website at the following link –</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mod-civilian-personnel-quarterly-report-2017</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-19T15:23:01.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715600/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715600/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715600/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Ministry of Defence: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many people are currently employed by his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715601","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-19","<p>The information on numbers of security passes currently valid is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-19T16:05:54.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715601/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715601/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715601/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Ministry of Defence: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many security passes giving access to his Department's premises are currently valid.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715602","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-18","<p>The Ministry of Defence is in the early stages of considering its future requirements management system. It is likely that existing Crown Commercial Services frameworks will be utilised to compete the future requirement, although the procurement process and associated timings are still being scoped.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","69938 ; 69940 ; 69946","2017-04-18T15:23:01.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715602/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715602/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715602/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Ministry of Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on what basis the choice of a requirements management system for his Department is made; and for what reasons there is not an open competition related to that system.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","69939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715603","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>The proportion of infantry enlistees who left the Army before completing their training in the last five years is shown below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion of Army Infantry Enlistees Who Did Not Complete Training</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>37%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>30%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>31%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>34%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>27%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes/Caveats:</p><p>The figures are for untrained Regular Army only and therefore exclude Gurkhas, Full Time Reserve Service, Mobilised Reserves, Army Reserve and all other Reserves.</p><p>The figures are for those personnel who enlisted into Infantry as untrained during the financial year and have subsequently outflowed prior to completion of training. Some of these personnel may have joined as Infantry and changed Arm/Service prior to leaving. There could be a small number of personnel who joined at the end of 2016 and may still be untrained.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-24T15:47:18.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715603/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715603/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715603/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Army: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of infantry enlistees have left the army before completing their training in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","69931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715604","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>Of those aged under 18 years of age on enlistment to the Regular Army as soldiers, the total number discharged under the category of 'defect in enlistment procedure' was 50 in 2015-16 and 30 in 2016-17. Totals have been rounded to the nearest '5'.</p><p>The specific reasons leading to defect in enlistment discharges are not recorded centrally, but include medical/health reasons, or previously undeclared criminal activity that has come to light after enlistment.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-24T15:28:06.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715604/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715604/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Army: Discharges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many army recruits aged under 18 were discharged for a defect on enlistment in the last two years for which figures are available; and what each of those defects were.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","69932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715605","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-19","<p>The Army is the UK's largest provider of apprenticeships as an employer.</p><p>All direct entry into The Infantry Training Centre Catterick Infantry are enrolled on a Level 2 apprenticeship, as part of the combined Combat Infantryman's Course. Those who have progressed from Army Foundation College Harrogate will already have enrolled onto the apprenticeship.</p><p>The requirement for a Level 2 apprenticeship is that apprentices achieve Level 1 Functional Skills in English and maths. Where the individual apprentice already holds Level 1 qualifications in English and maths or demonstrates a higher level of capability in those subjects, they are given the opportunity to work towards Level 2 during their apprenticeship. Of the Infantry soldiers in active learning in academic year 2015/16, 11% have gained Level 2 in maths and 12% have gained Level 2 in English within the Army. The number of personnel who work towards a Level 2 but who do not complete the exams is not centrally held.</p><p>Apprenticeships are not delivered at Army Training Centre, Pirbright as they are provided to recruits as part of their specialised trade training, and not during initial training.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-19T15:59:24.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715605/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715605/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of recruits at ITC Catterick and ATC Pirbright have enrolled for an intermediate level apprenticeship study for L2 qualifications in English and mathematics.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","69933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715606","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-19","<p>The Armed Forces take their responsibilities toward all their people extremely seriously, particularly where those personnel are under the age of 18. Disclosure and safeguarding checks are one aspect of our safeguarding provisions for those in the 16-18 age group. There is no legal requirement for disclosure and safeguarding checks to be carried out on all instructors at all phase 1 training sites, but the Department's policy is that such checks should be considered by the employing authorities of all Phase 1 and Phase 2 establishments.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-19T16:07:07.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715606/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715606/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Armed Forces: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether instructors at all phase 1 training sites where people aged under 18 are present are required to have disclosure and barring service clearance; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","69926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715607","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-24","<p>In the last five years no instructors from the Army Foundation College, Harrogate have failed the Army Staff and Leadership School (ASLS) course.</p><p>Information on those arriving and completing courses at ASLS without Disclosure and Barring Service (DBS) clearance is not held centrally and can be provided only at disproportionate cost. All permanent staff posts at Army Foundation College, Harrogate require DBS clearance. I refer the hon. Member to the answer my hon. Friend the Minister for Defence Veterans Reserves and Welfare (Mark Lancaster) gave on 9 December 2016 to Question 56016 to the hon. Member for Bridgend (Mrs Moon).</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-24T15:46:24.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715607/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715607/answer","20161209_56016_WQnA_extract_on_Army_Foundation_College_Vetting.pdf","20161209_56016_WQnA_extract_on_Army_Foundation_College_Vetting.pdf","56016 - WQnA extract on AFC: Vetting","56016 - WQnA extract on AFC: Vetting","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715607/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Army: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many prospective AFCH instructors (a) failed the Army Staff and Leadership School (ASLS), (b) arrived at the ASLS without disclosure and barring service (DBS) clearance and (c) completed ASLS without DBS clearance in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","69927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715608","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-19","<p>Following the 'Veterans' Transition Review' conducted by Lord Ashcroft KCMG PC in 2014, the Ministry of Defence implemented initiatives to ensure Early Service Leavers (ESLs) were offered resettlement support from the Career Transition Partnership Future Horizons (CTPFH) programme to tackle barriers to employment<strong>, </strong>education or further training.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold information on the number of ESLs who used CTP services between 1 October 2013 and 1 October 2015. Between 1 October 2015 and 31 March 2016, a total of 956 ESLs used the CTPFH programme (from a total of 1,144 eligible ESLs) which equates to a take-up rate of 84%.</p><p> </p><p>During financial year 2015-16, 11,163 Service Leavers (SLs) used CTP services, which includes the 956 ESLs who used the CTPFH programme between October 2015 and March 2016. Of the 599 SLs who used the CTPFH in this period and who had their employment information recorded, 449 (74%) were employed six months post-discharge.</p><p> </p><p>The vast majority of SLs who used the CTPFH were ESLs, although these figures also include some SLs who were eligible to access the Core Resettlement Programme or the Employment Support Programme but instead opted to use the CTPFH programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","69920 ; 69921","2017-04-19T15:53:17.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715608/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715608/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715608/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Veterans: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many and what proportion of early service leavers made use of the Career Transition Partnership in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","69930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715609","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-19","<p>In 2016-17 the proportion of those enlisted to the Regular Army as soldiers that were discharged prior to completion of Phase 2 training with grades A* to C, D to G in GCSE English and/or mathematics, and those without either, are as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Training Year 2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>English Language</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GCSE grades on entry</p></td><td><p>Proportion not completing training</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>A*-C</p></td><td><p>20%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>D-G</p></td><td><p>26%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>None</p></td><td><p>35%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Training Year 2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Mathematics</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GCSE grades on entry</p></td><td><p>Proportion not completing training</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>A*-C</p></td><td><p>19%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>D-G</p></td><td><p>26%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>None</p></td><td><p>34%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This does not include GCSE-equivalent qualifications.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-19T16:01:42.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715609/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715609/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Army: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of new army recruits with (a) grades A* to C, (b) grades D to G and (c) without any GCSE English and mathematics qualification left the army before completing phase 2 training in the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","69919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715610","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-19","<p>Following the 'Veterans' Transition Review' conducted by Lord Ashcroft KCMG PC in 2014, the Ministry of Defence implemented initiatives to ensure Early Service Leavers (ESLs) were offered resettlement support from the Career Transition Partnership Future Horizons (CTPFH) programme to tackle barriers to employment<strong>, </strong>education or further training.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold information on the number of ESLs who used CTP services between 1 October 2013 and 1 October 2015. Between 1 October 2015 and 31 March 2016, a total of 956 ESLs used the CTPFH programme (from a total of 1,144 eligible ESLs) which equates to a take-up rate of 84%.</p><p> </p><p>During financial year 2015-16, 11,163 Service Leavers (SLs) used CTP services, which includes the 956 ESLs who used the CTPFH programme between October 2015 and March 2016. Of the 599 SLs who used the CTPFH in this period and who had their employment information recorded, 449 (74%) were employed six months post-discharge.</p><p> </p><p>The vast majority of SLs who used the CTPFH were ESLs, although these figures also include some SLs who were eligible to access the Core Resettlement Programme or the Employment Support Programme but instead opted to use the CTPFH programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","69921 ; 69930","2017-04-19T15:53:17.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715610/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715610/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Veterans: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many and what proportion of service leavers making use of the Career Transition Partnership were early service leavers in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","69920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715611","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-19","<p>Following the 'Veterans' Transition Review' conducted by Lord Ashcroft KCMG PC in 2014, the Ministry of Defence implemented initiatives to ensure Early Service Leavers (ESLs) were offered resettlement support from the Career Transition Partnership Future Horizons (CTPFH) programme to tackle barriers to employment<strong>, </strong>education or further training.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold information on the number of ESLs who used CTP services between 1 October 2013 and 1 October 2015. Between 1 October 2015 and 31 March 2016, a total of 956 ESLs used the CTPFH programme (from a total of 1,144 eligible ESLs) which equates to a take-up rate of 84%.</p><p> </p><p>During financial year 2015-16, 11,163 Service Leavers (SLs) used CTP services, which includes the 956 ESLs who used the CTPFH programme between October 2015 and March 2016. Of the 599 SLs who used the CTPFH in this period and who had their employment information recorded, 449 (74%) were employed six months post-discharge.</p><p> </p><p>The vast majority of SLs who used the CTPFH were ESLs, although these figures also include some SLs who were eligible to access the Core Resettlement Programme or the Employment Support Programme but instead opted to use the CTPFH programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","69920 ; 69930","2017-04-19T15:53:17.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715611/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715611/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Veterans: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many and what proportion of early service leavers were in employment six months after discharge in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","69921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715612","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-19","<p>Between 1 April 2015 and 31 March 2016, 267 untrained Army personnel were medically discharged with musculoskeletal disorders and injuries, of these, 11 were under the age of 18. This is set against a backdrop of an untrained average yearly intake over the past three training years of 7,050 of which 1,790 are under 18.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-19T16:13:31.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715612/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715612/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Army: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of army recruits aged (a) under 18 and (b) over 18-years old were injured out of training in the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","69922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715613","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-19","<p>In training year 2015-16, 1,370 untrained Army personnel arrived at the Army Foundation College. During that same period 17 untrained Army personnel had a deliberate self-harm incident recorded at the College. Some of these personnel may have commenced training the previous year.</p><p>We take the duty of care to our personnel very seriously. Every unit has a comprehensive welfare system, which is widely publicised. The network of agencies includes chaplains, Equality and Diversity Advisers, Women's Royal Voluntary Service, and Unit Welfare Officers. Personnel also have access to the Army confidential helpline, and SpeakOut the Army's helpline.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-19T15:24:17.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715613/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715613/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Army: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many trainee soldiers appear in the Army Foundation College records as having committed self-harming behaviour in the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","69923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715614","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-19","<p>All allegations of bullying in the Armed Forces, including those made at initial Army training establishments, are taken seriously, investigated as appropriate and recorded.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-19T16:02:35.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715614/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715614/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Army: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether data is collected on the extent of bullying in initial army training establishments.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","69924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715615","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-19","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not hold this information in the format requested.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-19T15:51:31.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715615/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715615/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-30","Armed Forces: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many persons under the age of 18-years old resident in each (a) local authority area and (b) parliamentary constituency were recruited to the armed forces in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","69925"
